---
import DialecticDemo from '../components/DialecticDemo.svelte';
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>simcivics • dialectic substrate</title>
    <style>
      :root {
        --bg: #0b0b0c;
        --fg: #e6e6e8;
        --muted: #8a8a90;
        --accent: #3a8cff;
        --card: #141416;
        --border: #252528;
      }
      body {
        margin: 0;
        font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;
        background: var(--bg);
        color: var(--fg);
        line-height: 1.5;
      }
      .container {
        max-width: 960px;
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 2rem 1rem;
      }
      header {
        margin-bottom: 2rem;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
        padding-bottom: 1rem;
      }
      h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; }
      .tagline { color: var(--muted); font-size: 1rem; }
      .section { margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
      .card {
        background: var(--card);
        border: 1px solid var(--border);
        border-radius: 8px;
        padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
        margin-bottom: 1rem;
      }
      .meta { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--muted); }
      .claim { margin: 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); }
      .objection { background: #1a1a1f; padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 6px; margin: 0.5rem 0; }
      .principles {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(260px, 1fr));
        gap: 0.75rem;
      }
      .principle {
        background: var(--card);
        border: 1px solid var(--border);
        padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
        border-radius: 6px;
        font-size: 0.9rem;
      }
      code { font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; background: #1f1f22; padding: 0.1em 0.3em; border-radius: 3px; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <header>
        <h1>simcivics</h1>
        <p class="tagline">
          A substrate for dialectic in American civics.<br />
          Maps and syntheses that reward steelmanning, updating, and model-grounded opposition over rhetoric.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="section">
        <h2 style="margin-top:0">The operating idea</h2>
        <p>
          Current platforms optimize for engagement, status via performance, and zero-sum winning.
          This produces rhetoric. Dialectic (charitable opposition aimed at better models and occasional synthesis)
          is structurally disadvantaged.
        </p>
        <p>
          simcivics exists to invert that: make the <strong>persistent artifact</strong> a shared, versioned map of the issue;
          make <strong>opponent-endorsed charity</strong> and <strong>calibration on real subclaims</strong> the primary status signals;
          and attach <strong>simulations</strong> so that "my position assumes X" becomes inspectable and scoreable rather than handwaving.
        </p>
        <p class="meta">
          Complementary to projects that redirect attention toward higher-leverage civic work.
          Here the question is: when that attention is spent on contested policy and value questions, can the substrate itself be improved?
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="section">
        <h2>Design principles (from the thesis)</h2>
        <div class="principles">
          <div class="principle"><strong>Maps &gt; threads.</strong> The thing that improves over time is the shared representation, not the latest zinger.</div>
          <div class="principle"><strong>Charity is currency.</strong> A steelman the other side endorses is worth more than one they reject.</div>
          <div class="principle"><strong>Multi-dimensional reputation.</strong> Calibration, charity, update quality, synthesis influence, rigor — tracked separately.</div>
          <div class="principle"><strong>Structure enforced.</strong> Positions require explicit assumptions, strongest objections, and uncertainties by construction.</div>
          <div class="principle"><strong>Anti-herding visibility.</strong> Surface what distinguishes or bridges clusters (Polis spirit), not raw popularity.</div>
          <div class="principle"><strong>Simulation as first-class.</strong> Where claims rest on models, make the model runnable and comparable across positions.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section">
        <h2>Live toy example (seeded Issue)</h2>
        <p class="meta">
          This is not a real deliberation. It demonstrates the data model from <code>src/lib/domain.ts</code>:
          Issue → Positions with core claims + explicit steelman sections + cruxes + model attachments.
        </p>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="meta">ISSUE • municipal • housing + zoning</div>
          <h3 style="margin:0.25rem 0 0.5rem">How should Midtown zoning change to increase housing production while managing infrastructure strain?</h3>
          <div class="meta">Value conflicts: growth vs. neighborhood character • housing access vs. existing resident protections • short-term supply vs. long-term infrastructure capacity</div>
        </div>

        <DialecticDemo client:load />
      </div>

      <div class="section">
        <h2>Core entities (current model)</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Issue</strong> — the container with scope, value conflicts, status.</li>
          <li><strong>Position</strong> — versioned, with coreClaims, assumptions, evidenceRefs, <em>anticipatedObjections</em> (the steelman field with endorsement flag), cruxes, attachedModelRefs, synthesisOf.</li>
          <li><strong>Claim</strong> — typed (empirical/predictive/value/causal_model) so we know how to score and attach things.</li>
          <li><strong>Crux</strong> — load-bearing disagreement points with status.</li>
          <li><strong>Evidence</strong> — with quality tiers and relevance notes.</li>
          <li><strong>Simulation</strong> — params + lastRun, embodying specific Positions' assumptions.</li>
          <li><strong>DialecticSession</strong> — the ritual with phases: presentation → cross_steelman → crux_identification → focused_work → synthesis_attempt.</li>
          <li><strong>Endorsement</strong> — typed signals (fair_steelman_of_my_side, would_adopt_this_synthesis, etc.). These move reputation and visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Reputation</strong> — calibration, charity, updateQuality, synthesisInfluence, rigor (no single karma).</li>
          <li><strong>LiveMap</strong> — the promoted current best structure for an Issue.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="meta">
          See <code>ARCHITECTURE.md</code> for the full rationale and how these are meant to be used in incentive design and UI.
        </p>
      </div>

      <footer style="margin-top:3rem; padding-top:1rem; border-top:1px solid var(--border); color:var(--muted); font-size:0.85rem;">
        Early scaffolding. The thesis and architecture documents are the primary artifacts right now.
        Implementation must be judged against whether it makes dialectic the locally rational strategy for participants seeking durable status or influence inside the system.
      </footer>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
